 Silvio Berlusconi, the charismatic and controversial Italian statesman who left an indelible mark on Italy’s political landscape, passed away on June 12, 2023 at age 86. Berlusconi, a media tycoon turned prime minister, was known for his flamboyant style, captivating rhetoric, and tumultuous personal life. He was for a long time the owner of one of Italy’s most successful football clubs, AC Milan from 1986 to 2017. Born on September 29, 1936, in Milan, Italy, Berlusconi was raised in a middle-class family. His father, a bank employee, instilled in him a strong work ethic and a desire for success. Berlusconi’s journey to power began in the realm of business, where he established an empire that spanned television, publishing, and advertising. His media conglomerate, Mediaset, brought him immense wealth and influence, positioning him as one of Italy’s most formidable figures. In 1994, Berlusconi made his foray into politics, founding Forza Italia (Go Italy), a center-right political party. With his media prowess, he orchestrated a captivating campaign that resonated with many Italians, promising prosperity and a fresh approach to governance. In 1994, he became the Prime Minister of Italy for the first time, initiating a tumultuous tenure marked by scandals, controversies, and constant battles with the judiciary. Berlusconi’s political career was a rollercoaster ride, characterized by his charisma, sharp wit, and ability to connect with the masses. His public appearances were often theatrical, with his distinctive mane of silver hair and a contagious smile that could disarm even his staunchest opponents. He employed his media empire to great effect, dominating the airwaves and shaping public opinion through his television channels. Read also: Former Italian PM, Silvio Berlusconi, dies at 86 However, Berlusconi’s time in office was also marred by numerous legal troubles. He faced charges of corruption, bribery, tax evasion, and other financial improprieties. Despite his legal battles, he retained a loyal base of supporters who admired his unapologetic audacity and perceived ability to protect Italian interests against external pressures. Berlusconi’s controversial personal life was widely covered by the media, both nationally and internationally. His high-profile divorce from his first wife, Carla Elvira Dall’Oglio, captivated the public’s attention. Later, he married Veronica Lario, and their relationship became a subject of constant scrutiny. Berlusconi’s reputation as a womanizer was legendary, and his lavish parties and alleged encounters with young women fueled public fascination and fueled the tabloid headlines. Throughout his political career, Berlusconi pursued an agenda centered on economic reform, tax cuts, and promoting Italy’s global standing. However, his policies often faced criticism for favoring his own business interests and failing to address systemic issues such as corruption and economic inequality. Berlusconi’s impact on Italian politics cannot be understated. He reshaped the country’s political landscape, polarizing public opinion and dividing the nation. His populist rhetoric appealed to a significant segment of the population, while others viewed him as a symbol of the corrupt establishment. He was both loved and reviled, admired and despised—a true figure of contention in Italian society. In 2011, following a series of political setbacks and a struggling economy, Berlusconi resigned as prime minister. His departure marked the end of an era, but his influence continued to loom large over Italian politics. Despite his controversies and legal battles, he remained a potent force, even in his later years. Silvio Berlusconi will be remembered as a figure who shaped Italian politics with his charisma, ambition, and controversial persona. He leaves behind a complicated legacy, one that encompasses both political achievements and personal shortcomings. Whether admired or admonished, he undeniably left an indelible mark on the nation he called home.